An undersea magnitude 7.4 earthquake struck off northern Indonesia on April 1, toppling buildings in Manado and killing at least one person. It generated 75cm tsunami waves, prompting thousands to flee homes. Monitoring continues for aftershocks and damage assessments in a seismically active region.

Israeli air defenses intercepted three waves of Iranian missiles near Tel Aviv early April 2, lightly wounding several people after sirens sounded nationwide. This followed President Trump's April 1 primetime address claiming U.S. goals neared in the Iran war and threatening to bomb Iran. Separately, Britain hosted a virtual meeting of 35 countries on April 3 to plan reopening the Strait of Hormuz, blocked by the U.S.-Israel-Iran war and affecting 20% of global oil trade. In eastern Congo, Rwanda-backed rebels overran troops and entered the city of Goma amid gunfire and shelling, displacing over 1 million people according to UN estimates and threatening a key aid hub.

NASA launched the Artemis II mission from Kennedy Space Center on April 1 with three American astronauts and one Canadian for a 10-day lunar flyby, the first crewed Moon mission in 50 years. The U.S. lifted sanctions on Venezuela acting president Delcy Rodríguez after capturing Nicolás Maduro, easing economic pressures and impacting oil markets. A federal appeals court rejected the HUD plan to redirect homelessness funding to sobriety programs, affecting 600,000 unsheltered Americans; HUD must keep current priorities. The FDA approved the daily obesity pill Foundayo as a non-injection alternative to Wegovy. Hundreds of thousands of Palestinians crossed into northern Gaza after Israel resolved a hostage release impasse. Senate Republicans scheduled a Thursday vote on funding most DHS operations through September to end the record partial government shutdown affecting 200,000 employees, with House follow-up planned.
